<%# Public home / landing page. STUFF.md #13 + #14.
    GET / always renders this view; the hero branches on @returning_user
    (true when ReadStateStore has any activity in the DB) — first-time
    visitors get the marketing pitch; returning users get a "Welcome
    back" hero with stats + top picks. Feature cards stay below either
    hero. /dashboard links carry data-turbo="false" so Chart.js inits
    cleanly on a full document load. %>

<% if @returning_user %>
  <%# STUFF.md #14 — personalized hero for returning users. No cookie:
      we infer "returning" from the presence of any read_state activity
      in the DB (any opened/bookmarked/feedback'd article). The pillars
      below remain visible so the vision is still on the page. %>
  <section class="home-hero home-hero-returning">
    <div class="home-hero-text">
      <h1>Welcome back.</h1>
      <p class="home-tagline">
        You have <strong><%= @stats[:unread] %></strong> unread,
        <strong><%= @stats[:bookmarks] %></strong> bookmarked
        across <strong><%= @stats[:articles] %></strong> articles.
        <% if @latest_triage && @latest_triage['generated_at'] %>
          Last triage <%= relative_time(@latest_triage['generated_at']) %>.
        <% end %>
      </p>
      <div class="home-cta">
        <a class="btn-primary" href="/articles?sort=relevance&amp;state=unread">Read your top picks &rarr;</a>
        <a class="home-cta-secondary" href="/dashboard" data-turbo="false">Open dashboard &rarr;</a>
      </div>
      <% if (@top_unread || []).any? %>
        <ul class="home-hero-picks">
          <% @top_unread.first(3).each do |article| %>
            <li>
              <a href="/article/<%= article['uid'] %>"><%= h(article['title']) %></a>
            </li>
          <% end %>
        </ul>
      <% end %>
    </div>
    <div class="home-hero-image">
      <img src="/img/home/dashboard.png" alt="Dashboard view: article counts, activity chart, top feeds and tags." loading="lazy">
    </div>
  </section>
<% else %>
  <section class="home-hero">
    <div class="home-hero-text">
      <h1>Stop swivel-chairing between 50 sites.</h1>
      <p class="home-tagline">
        An RSS reader that <strong>ranks</strong>, <strong>summarizes</strong>,
        and <strong>triages</strong> your feed for you. Self-hosted,
        single-user, no analytics, no algorithmic agenda.
      </p>
      <div class="home-cta">
        <a class="btn-primary" href="/dashboard" data-turbo="false">Open dashboard &rarr;</a>
        <a class="home-cta-secondary" href="/about">What this is &rarr;</a>
      </div>
      <p class="home-hero-meta">
        Free &middot; Open source &middot; Your data lives on your disk
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="home-hero-image">
      <img src="/img/home/dashboard.png" alt="Dashboard view: article counts, activity chart, top feeds and tags." loading="lazy">
    </div>
  </section>
<% end %>

<section class="home-features">
  <article class="home-feature">
    <div class="home-feature-body">
      <h2>🌐 One inbox for everything you read</h2>
      <p>
        Add a curated set of 25+ feeds in one click, or bulk-import OPML.
        Tech, sports, and podcasts share a single ranked queue.
        Stop opening twelve tabs every morning.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <article class="home-feature home-feature-with-image">
    <div class="home-feature-body">
      <h2>🎯 Ranked for you</h2>
      <p>
        Every article gets a personal score based on what you've bookmarked,
        thumbs-upped, or skipped. The ranker honours your topic preferences —
        sports feedback won't pollute your tech queue, and vice versa.
        Sort: <code>?sort=relevance</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="home-feature-image">
      <img src="/img/home/for-you.png" alt="Articles list sorted by personal relevance." loading="lazy">
    </div>
  </article>

  <article class="home-feature home-feature-with-image">
    <div class="home-feature-body">
      <h2>🧠 AI-assisted triage</h2>
      <p>
        One Claude call (Sonnet 4.6) classifies every unread article into
        <strong>Must read</strong>, <strong>Optional</strong>, or <strong>Skip</strong>,
        with a one-sentence rationale that cites <em>your</em> past behaviour:
        "matches your bookmarked Ruby work," "topic you've previously demoted."
        Three runs nightly via cron — one per topic.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="home-feature-image">
      <img src="/img/home/triage.png" alt="AI triage page showing Must read / Optional / Skip groups with rationale." loading="lazy">
    </div>
  </article>

  <article class="home-feature home-feature-with-image">
    <div class="home-feature-body">
      <h2>✍️ Summaries you can skim</h2>
      <p>
        Every article gets an extractive summary inline. One click adds a full
        Claude summary cached on the row, so revisits don't re-spend tokens.
        Skim mode hides the noise so you can clear 100 unread in minutes.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="home-feature-image">
      <img src="/img/home/digest.png" alt="Daily digest page with cached Claude summary at the top." loading="lazy">
    </div>
  </article>

  <article class="home-feature home-feature-with-image">
    <div class="home-feature-body">
      <h2>🎧 Podcasts that follow you</h2>
      <p>
        A persistent mini-player at the bottom of every page keeps audio
        playing as you navigate. Episodes appear in the same queue as
        articles, with listened-percent + speed-control + skip-15s.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="home-feature-image">
      <img src="/img/home/podcasts.png" alt="Podcasts page with subscribed shows and recent episodes." loading="lazy">
    </div>
  </article>

  <article class="home-feature home-feature-with-image">
    <div class="home-feature-body">
      <h2>🏈 Sports — same engine, different domain</h2>
      <p>
        Scores, league standings, calendar export (iCal subscribe), and follows
        for teams + individual tennis players. Articles mentioning your followed
        entities surface on their detail page automatically.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="home-feature-image">
      <img src="/img/home/sports.png" alt="Sports landing page with score tiles and league sections." loading="lazy">
    </div>
  </article>
</section>

<section class="home-narrative">
  <h2>Information comes to you, not the other way around.</h2>
  <p>
    Most of us spend an hour a day swivel-chairing — Hacker News, then The Verge,
    then Lobsters, then five team-specific blogs, then a podcast app, then back
    to the top because "did I check that one yet?". The platforms call this
    <em>engagement</em>. It's just lost time.
  </p>
  <p>
    Tech Feed Reader inverts that. You declare what you care about. The server
    pulls every feed every ten minutes. Claude triages overnight. The ranker
    learns from your clicks. By the time you open the dashboard, the work is
    done — you read, you skim, you skip.
  </p>
  <p>
    The algorithm works for <strong>you</strong>, not against you. Nothing is
    optimised for retention. Nothing is monetised. There's no feed of someone
    else's choosing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="home-final-cta">
  <h2>Open it up.</h2>
  <p>
    The dashboard is one click away. Or read about the philosophy first.
  </p>
  <div class="home-cta">
    <a class="btn-primary" href="/dashboard" data-turbo="false">Open dashboard &rarr;</a>
    <a class="home-cta-secondary" href="/about">About this project &rarr;</a>
  </div>
</section>
